"Reassessing Resume Gaps: A Shift in Perspective\n\nTo Employers:\nWhen evaluating candidates, it's crucial to look beyond resume gaps and recognize the inherent value they may bring. Inspired by HBR, consider these tips for assessing career breaks:\n- Inquire about the story behind the gap to uncover valuable skills, resilience, or renewed direction.\n- Emphasize growth over gaps, acknowledging how candidates use this time to upskill, volunteer, or reflect on their career trajectory.\n- Acknowledge the evolving norm of career breaks post-pandemic, understanding its impact on workers' priorities.\n- Value authenticity in candidates who address gaps with honesty and confidence, traits they may bring to your team.\n\nRemember, a resume gap signifies more than a pause—it often symbolizes a period of growth, learning, or life management. Keeping an open mind could lead you to your next exceptional hire.\n\nTo Job Seekers:\n- Address resume gaps directly, focusing on the positive aspects and how they enriched your life or skills.\n- Highlight personal growth during the gap, showcasing volunteer work, new skills acquired, or realigned goals.\n- Tailor your explanation to the role, emphasizing how your experiences strengthen your candidacy.\n- Confidently own your unique career journey, understanding that a gap doesn't define you; it's how you navigate and learn from it that matters.\n\nHave you considered the untapped potential of resume gaps? Individuals with extended breaks have secured remarkable roles by leveraging their distinctive strengths and experiences. Share your insights on uncovering the value within these gaps below!\n\n\n\n♻️ Repost to inspire someone\n🔔 Follow Kumud Deepali R. for daily hiring and motivational posts!\n…more"
"12 ways to email like a boss (even if you aren’t one)\n\nBeing too nice in emails weakens your message.\nIt makes people brush off your requests.\n\n----\n\nHere’s a tool to create a professional resume that stands out and passes ATS filters*:\n👉🏻\n\n----\n\nHere are 12 email responses to sound more confident:\n\nAddressing a Delay\n❌ ""Sorry for the delay.""\n✅ ""Thank you for your patience.""\n\nAcknowledging a Mistake\n❌ ""Sorry I missed that.""\n✅ ""Thank you for bringing this to my attention.""\n\nResponding to Appreciation\n❌ ""No worries.""\n✅ ""I’m always happy to assist.""\n\nFollowing Up on Progress\n❌ ""Just checking in.""\n✅ ""When can I expect an update?""\n\n\nEnsuring Clarity\n❌ ""Hopefully that makes sense?""\n✅ ""Please let me know if you have any questions.""\n\nConsidering New Ideas\n❌ ""Maybe we can consider...""\n✅ ""Let's explore additional options.""\n\nRequesting Feedback\n❌ ""Let me know what you think.""\n✅ ""I’d appreciate your feedback.""\n\nAsking for a Review\n❌ ""If it’s not too much trouble...""\n✅ ""Could you please take a look and advise?""\n\n\nSetting Expectations\n❌ ""I’ll try to get it done by Friday.""\n✅ ""I will have it done by Friday.""\n\nClarifying a Point\n❌ ""I’m not sure, but...""\n✅ ""Based on my understanding...""\n\nAddressing a Concern\n❌ ""I’m a little worried about that.""\n✅ ""There are some concerns we should address.""\n\nProposing a Meeting\n❌ ""Let me know when you’re free.""\n✅ ""Would you be available to discuss this?""\n\nThe right words can change how others respond to you.\nChoose them wisely and see better results.\n\nWhat else would you add?\nLet me know in the comments.\n\n\n♻️ Repost and follow for more expert communication tips\n\nCredit: Lauren Murrell, for the inspiration.\n…more"
