"As a recruiter, I view resumes fairly often 😋\n\nHehe, if I can, just a few tips and ideas for those on the employment search?\n(I am by no means a PRO, this purely my opinion from patterns I and my team see.)\n\nAnd by all means, ignore everything I say... we enjoy a good laugh 😁😁\n\n\nHonestly, I would like to spend more time talking with YOU rather than asking about all the gaps or confusion that comes from unfinished or empty resumes.\n(I hope this finds the right audience 😬!)\n\nSo...\n\n1. INTRO - We love an intro! Every Indeed manufactured resume looks generic with the ""will relocate anywhere"" which, frankly, isn't true.\nTell me about you and what your goal is in seeking a new position! This helps me get a head start when I get a blurb about what you want and where you are at in your search.\n\n2. DATES - For the love of all things holy and good and...\nClean up your dates, don't leave gaps, and explain temp, contract, or seasonal jobs. We automatically rule out poor job longevity so if you explain the reason behind short-term positions, boom!\n\n3. CONTEXT - Give me context please! Who are you?!\nWhether you work at a Warehouse, in Construction, or got involved in Manufacturing... it seems that unless you are OCD, most of the time there is a LACK of information on what you actually did on your resume. Keep in mind- sometimes title doesn't match responsibilities. Add leadership skills and certificates to your timeline so we can really see what you have to offer!\n\n4. ERRORS- *clears throat. We pay attention to spelling and grammar errors. I mean, we're here to help update all that for your future employer, but if you catch it, make the change! This includes resume gaps that we want to understand AND inconsistency in punctuation, font, and bullet points.\nTake a second to review before uploading.\n\n5. SKILLS - Don't let a resume generator do all the work! I want to know what YOU specifically can do and that is not always given proper honor when you allow a hiring site to guess your skills based on your previous roles. Really think about what you have accrued besides the typical additions of ""time management"" and ""customer service."" We know you have more to offer!\n\nJust a few thoughts! We would love to give you and your future employer the BEST CHANCE in connecting.\n…more"
"The design, layout, and content of your resume are essential for capturing the reader's attention in the first 20 to 30 seconds. It’s important to approach this task with a clear strategy, focusing on highlighting your skills and experience in a concise and engaging way. Here are a few tips to help you craft the perfect resume:\n\n1. Highlight your accomplishments: If you cut costs, increased revenue, delivered projects ahead of time, or broke company records, your resume is the perfect place to highlight these achievements using numbers and percentages to demonstrate your impact.\n2. Call out the value you would bring to the target company: Just like in sports, where the value of a new player is debated, your resume is the place to highlight the value you can bring to a potential employer, using the language that aligns with the job you're applying for.\n3. Identify the ways you help solve the company’s challenges: Just like an infomercial highlights a product’s strengths to solve a problem, your resume should showcase your professional assets and demonstrate how you can address the challenges of the company you're applying to.\n\nThe right job for you is out there. We can help get you to it\n\nClick the link below to check out our blog!\n\n\n\n…more"
"Is your resume starting to resemble a novel? 📚 Let's trim that epic down to a compelling short story!\n\nHere's how:\n1. Prioritize the Last 10-15 Years: Focus on your most recent experience; hiring managers are more interested in what you've done lately.\n2. Highlight Achievements, Not Just Duties: Showcase your impact with quantifiable results—think revenue growth, cost savings, or process improvements.\n3. Remove Outdated Skills: If it's no longer relevant (e.g., obsolete software), leave it out.\n4. Use a Hybrid Resume Format: A skills-focused format helps showcase expertise before listing work history.\n5. Tailor for Each Job: Only include roles that are directly relevant.\nRemember, your resume should be a highlight reel, not a documentary. Keep it concise, relevant, and future-focused to show why you're the best fit for today's job market.\n\nWhat's your biggest challenge in keeping your resume concise? Let's discuss in the comments!\n\n…more"
