"✨📄 Resume Building 101: Stand Out in 20 Seconds 📄✨\nDid you know that employers typically spend only 20 to 30 seconds looking at a resume? Make every second count with these top tips:\n1. Choose the Right Format: Highlight your experiences, skills, and abilities in a format that suits you best. A reverse chronological order is often effective, listing your most recent activities first.\n2. Keep It Concise: Aim for a one-page resume with consistent formatting. Use bullet points and simple sentences for clarity.\n3. Be Honest: Always be truthful. Employers verify information, and honesty is key.\n4. Visual Appeal: Make your resume visually appealing to grab attention.\n5. Tailor Your Resume: Customize your resume for each job application. Highlight relevant skills and experiences.\n6. Clear Objective: Include a clear resume objective to give employers insight into your interests.\n7. Action Verbs: Start sentences with powerful action verbs to make your points impactful.\n8. Error-Free: Ensure your resume is free of grammatical, spelling, punctuation, and typographical errors.\n9. Use Keywords: Incorporate industry-specific keywords and phrases to make your resume relevant to recruiters. For example, if you're an Accounting major, include 'CPA Eligible by May 2025'.\n10. Show Leadership and Achievements: Highlight any leadership roles, achievements, and organizational involvement. Make sure these are also visible on your LinkedIn profile.\nRemember, a well-crafted resume can make a significant difference in your job application process. Let's make your resume shine! 🌟\n\n…more"
"The Truth Behind 6 Resume Myths 🔊 \n\nThere’s a lot of resume “wisdom” floating around the internet—but not all of it is accurate. Let’s bust six of the most common resume myths and set the record straight:\n\n1. Your Resume Must Be One Page\nNot true! If you have substantial experience, it’s okay to go up to two pages. What matters is how relevant and concise your content is.\n\n2. Gaps in Your Resume Are Dealbreakers\nLife happens! As long as you address gaps confidently and show how you stayed active or grew during them, it won’t sink your chances.\n\n3. You Always Need References\nNope! Employers typically ask for references after you’ve made it through the initial stages. Keep them on hand but off your resume.\n\n4. Your Resume Should Be ""Unique""\nA flashy, one-of-a-kind resume isn’t necessary unless you’re in a creative field. Focus on clarity and relevance instead of gimmicks.\n\n5. You Have to List Your Full Address\nThe days of snail mail are over! Just list your city and state—no need for your full address.\n\n6. Dates and Employer Names Aren’t Important\nThink again! Hiring managers want to know where you worked and for how long. Dates and employer names give your experience credibility.\n…more"
