"Tip of the Week: Your Resume Should Be a Movie Trailer, Not the Whole Script\n\nIf your resume reads like a generic job description, we have a problem. Hiring managers don’t want to see a list of what you were supposed to do—they want to see what you actually did.\n\nSaying “Managed cloud infrastructure” is the resume equivalent of saying you “existed” at work. Instead, try “Optimized cloud resources to cut hosting costs by 35% while improving system uptime to 99.98%.”\n\nSee the difference? Numbers, results, and real impact make you stand out.\n\nThink of your resume like a movie trailer—it should hook the audience, highlight the best moments, and leave them wanting more. What projects did you crush? What problems did you solve? How did your work make life easier, faster, or more efficient for your team? If your resume doesn’t make hiring managers excited to learn more, it’s time for a rewrite.\n\nHiring managers want problem-solvers, not a recap of job duties. Show them the action, the impact, and the results.\n\nWhat’s the best resume tip that helped you land an interview? Drop it in the comments!\n…more"
