"Your IT/tech job descriptions might be turning candidates away. 🛑\n\nThis is how to fix them! ✅\n\n➡️ 1. Start with a clear job title\nAvoid jargon or creative titles that confuse candidates. A straightforward job title like ""Software Engineer"" performs better in search results and aligns with candidate expectations.\n\n➡️ 2. Include a strong opening summary\nSummarize the role in 2-3 sentences. Focus on the core purpose of the job and how it contributes to the company’s goals, keeping it concise and engaging.\n\n➡️ 3. Outline key responsibilities clearly\nList the main tasks in bullet points. Be specific to avoid ambiguity—avoid general phrases like ""handle IT projects"" and specify the exact responsibilities.\n\n➡️ 4. Focus on day-to-day activities\nPaint a picture of a typical day in the role. This helps candidates visualize the job and assess if it's the right fit for them.\n\n➡️ 5. Specify required skills and technologies\nClearly list must-have technical skills, such as Python, SQL, or AWS. This filters candidates early and saves time for both parties.\n\n➡️ 6. Differentiate between ‘required’ and ‘preferred’ skills\nClearly label ""must-have"" versus ""nice-to-have"" skills. This helps attract qualified applicants while keeping the door open for those who may have potential.\n\n➡️ 7. Set realistic expectations for experience levels\nBe precise about the experience level required—whether it's entry-level or senior. Avoid broad terms like ""junior"" or ""experienced"" without clear year-based guidelines.\n\n➡️ 8. Explain the purpose of the role\nDescribe why the role exists and how it fits into the company's broader goals. This provides context and meaning, motivating the right candidates to apply.\n\n➡️ 9. Highlight career growth opportunities\nMention internal development programs or career paths. Candidates want to know how they can progress within your company, especially in a fast-paced industry like IT.\n\n➡️ 10. Provide a clear reporting structure\nState who the candidate will report to. This helps candidates understand where the role fits in the organizational hierarchy and clarifies team dynamics.\n\n... and 14 further must-read tips in the carousel below!\n\n…more"
"Did you recently get passed over for a role you thought you were a perfect fit for? Job hunting can be a challenging journey, and rejection, while tough, is often part of the process. Instead of letting frustration take over, take a step back and assess your approach. Are there areas where you could refine your strategy? Below are a few insights that might help you turn things around and boost your chances for success.\n\n1. Are You Aiming Too High?\nOne common mistake candidates make is applying for roles that may be slightly out of reach. It’s natural to want to push for the next level in your career, but are your qualifications truly aligned with the position you’re applying for?\n\nIf you find yourself consistently passed over for roles that require more experience or a broader skill set, it might be time to reassess and realign. Consider seeking a company with a clear advancement policy or a position that will help bridge the gap between where you are now and where you want to go. Remember: career growth is a marathon, not a sprint.\n\n2. Have You Updated and Tailored Your Resume?\nYour resume is the first impression you make on potential employers. Have you taken the time to thoroughly update it before submitting your applications? A rushed, generic resume could be the reason you’re not getting callbacks.\n\nThink carefully about the content you’re showcasing. Are you just listing broad job duties, or are you clearly communicating your achievements and the value you've added in your previous roles? Employers want to see specific examples of how you’ve contributed to the success of your past organizations. Instead of simply stating “responsible for managing a team,” try adding more depth: “Led a team of 8 to successfully implement a project that resulted in a 15% increase in operational efficiency.”\n\nRefine each bullet point, focusing on accomplishments and measurable outcomes that highlight your unique value.\n\n3. Are You Preparing for Interviews?\nWinging it simply won’t cut it. The competition is fierce, and preparation is key. If you’re not taking the time to prepare for interviews, you’re missing out on one of your best chances to shine.\n\nThink about your most significant career achievements—those moments that truly made an impact at your previous companies. Be ready to share specific metrics, numbers, and examples that demonstrate your value.\n\nIt’s also important to keep your answers concise. Hiring managers often have limited time, so make sure you’re answering questions thoroughly without going off on tangents. Practice telling your stories in a clear, impactful way that highlights your expertise while remaining focused on the relevant details.\n\n4. Bonus: Explore Interview Tips from Experts\nIf you’re feeling stuck or unsure about how to best prepare for interviews, consider checking out resources like Janet Jones’ profile for a series of valuable tips on acing interviews.\n…more"
