"Your resume gets 6 seconds. \n\nSIX SECONDS. That’s all recruiters need...\n\nTo decide if your CV lands\nin the “no thanks” pile.\n\nIf your resume is sending the wrong signals,\nit’s game over—before you’ve even started.\n\nHere’s how to fix it fast:\n\n1. ""I Didn’t Read the Job Posting.""\n🔴 Red Flag: Clichés like “detail-oriented” or “team player.”\n🟢 Fix It: Mirror the job description. Use keywords and highlight specific achievements.\n\n2. ""I’m Living in the Past.""\n🔴 Red Flag: Listing ancient or irrelevant experience.\n🟢 Fix It: Focus on the last 10 years. Keep it lean & relevant.\n\n3. ""I’m Afraid of Technology.""\n🔴 Red Flag: No mention of tools or platforms.\n🟢 Fix It: Add your tech stack—Excel, Salesforce, or certifications. Digital fluency is mandatory.\n\n4. ""I’m Hiding Something.""\n🔴 Red Flag: Unexplained employment gaps.\n🟢 Fix It: Fill the gaps—showcase freelancing, volunteering, or upskilling. Control the narrative.\n\n5. ""I Don’t Sweat the Details.""\n🔴 Red Flag: Typos, inconsistent formatting, outdated info.\n🟢 Fix It: Use Grammarly. Polished resumes show you care.\n\n6. ""I Have No Results to Show.""\n🔴 Red Flag: Vague phrases like “managed a team” or “responsible for projects.”\n🟢 Fix It: Quantify everything:\n“Boosted sales by 25%” > “Managed a team.”\n\n7. ""I’m Just Sending This Everywhere.""\n🔴 Red Flag: Generic resumes sent to every job.\n🟢 Fix It: Highlight wins that match the job description.\n\n8. ""I’m Desperate.""\n🔴 Red Flag: Applying for every job under the sun.\n🟢 Fix It: Stay focused. Align your resume to roles that tell one clear story.\n\n🔥 Your Resume = Your Pitch.\n\nIf it’s not selling your story,\nit’s time for a rewrite.\n\nWhat is your resume really saying about you?\n\n♻️ Share this to help someone today!\n🔔 And followfor more.\n…more"
"Here are my top tips to make your resume stand out!! The goal is clarity and readability. A well-organised, professional resume creates a positive first impression and helps employers quickly see why you're a strong candidate.\n\nOver the next few weeks, I'll also provide tips on what to avoid including in your resume and seek your input on some debatable topics you might believe should be included.\n\nSTART WITH THE BASICS - Create a clear, professional header with your name, in a larger font, (your header is the first thing employers will notice) and include in a smaller font your phone number and email for easy readability.\n\nSUMMARY - Include a brief summary under your header highlighting your skills, experience, and career goals to showcase and make a strong first impression that you’re the right fit for the job.\n\nSKILLS - Highlight relevant expertise here, tailoring them to the job description and including transferable skills.\n\nHIGHLIGHT YOUR ACHIEVEMENTS AND EDUCATION- List your degrees, certifications, courses, languages, awards, key achievements, professional memberships, accreditations, and volunteer work.\n\nSOFTWARE – List all software programs you’ve used in a separate section under your achievements.\n\nCAREER SUMMARY TABLE – Provide a VERY BRIEF snapshot of your past roles under your listed software, including job title, company, and dates worked. Start with your most recent roles, and include your expanded detailed tasks separately on the following pages.\n\nEMPLOYMENT HISTORY\n⦿ Include company name, job title, promotions, exact dates, and if a permanent or a contract role.\n⦿ Keep your resume concise - 1-3 pages max, or up to 4 if you have over 20 years of experience. List the last 15 years of experience in reverse order, condensing older roles past 15 years unless they are relevant to the job.\n⦿ Dot point tasks - Write in first person without ""I,"" e.g., “Scheduled and organised client appointments.”\n⦿ Make it precise and measurable - saying “increased sales by 20%” is more impactful than “improved sales”, instead of “updating clients,” say “updated 60 clients weekly.”\n⦿ Include specific skills and highlight keywords from the job description in your resume to showcase your relevant experience.\n⦿ Briefly explain employment gaps, whether due to travel, study, COVID, redundancy, family, or other reasons.\n\nFORMATTING - Use a consistent 10-12 pt font, bold headers only, bullet points for tasks, and a professional font like Times New Roman or Arial. If using lines, keep them thin and light-coloured.\n\nPROOFREAD – Print or read your resume aloud to spot errors, and have a detail-oriented friend review it.\n\nFINISHING TOUCHES - Name it properly, using your name followed by ""Resume” and save your resume as a PDF to maintain its format.\n\n""MOST IMPORTANTLY"", BE HONEST - Honesty is key to your resume. Dishonesty can harm your chances and reputation. Stay truthful!\n…more"
