"Here are some common resume pitfalls transitioning military job seekers fall into:\n\n🚩 1. The ‘One-Size-Fits-All’ Resume\n\nUsing the same generic resume for every job application is a surefire way to get ignored.\n\nSolution: Tailor your resume to each job by aligning your skills and experience with the job description.\n\n🚩 2. No Metrics, No Proof\n\nSaying you ""improved processes"" in the military is vague. Saying you ""increased efficiency by 30% and reduced costs by $50K"" is impactful.\n\nSolution: Use quantifiable achievements to show your value.\n\n🚩 3. The Job Description Copy-Paste Trap\n\nRegurgitating your job duties from a military or corporate role isn't compelling.\n\nSolution: Translate responsibilities into accomplishments. Hiring managers want to know how you made an impact, not just what you were assigned to do. Make sure to use action verbs, metrics, and show results.\n\n🚩 4. Too Much Military/Career Jargon\n\nDon't use military jargon and acronyms that civilians don't understand.\nIf your resume reads like a mission report, it won’t resonate with civilian recruiters.\n\nSolution: Simplify terminology and explain how your skills transfer to the industry you’re targeting.\n\n🚩 5. Keyword Deficiency\n\nMany resumes get rejected by recruiters because you are not proving how you meet the skills nor address the key words listed in the job description.\n\nSolution: Don't just list all of your previous job responsibilities, use relevant industry keywords and skills from the job description, and SHOW how you've done THAT thing they want you to know how to do.\n\nA resume isn’t just a piece of paper; it’s your personal marketing document.\n\nAvoid these mistakes, and you’ll get closer to landing an interview.\n\nMaloney out! ✌\n\n\n\n\n…more"
"I hear so many engineers asking about ATS-friendly resumes, so I am going to break it down for you today!\n\nLet's use these tips for writing an ATS-friendly resume:\n\n✅ Use standard headings:\n- Stick to common headings like “Work Experience,” “Education,” & ""Skills.”\n\n✅ Keep formatting simple:\n- Avoid complex layouts, tables, and graphics that could confuse ATS systems.\n\n✅ Incorporate keywords:\n- Strategically incorporate relevant keywords from the job description to ensure your resume matches the job requirements.\n- Try to match 70-80% of job description language\n\n✅ Use a professional & readable font:\n-  Stick to fonts like Arial, Times New Roman, or Calibri to ensure readability.\n\n✅ Tailor each resume:\n- Customize your resume for each job application to reflect the specific job requirements.\n\n✅ Quantify relevant experiences:\n- Highlight measurable achievements and impactful projects.\n\nCritical resume mistakes to avoid:\n\n❌ Omit personal details:\n- Do not include details like age, marital status, or photographs.\n\n❌ Avoid complex designs:\n- Skip colourful, overly creative layouts that distract from the main content.\n\n❌ Exclude irrelevant experiences:\n- Focus only on relevant, recent experience to keep your resume concise.\n\n❌ Keep graduate resumes short:\n- For fresh graduates, limit your resume to one page.\n\nYour resume is your first impression, make sure it is clear, optimized, and ATS-friendly to increase your chances of landing an interview.\n\n✅ Focus on readability, relevance, and measurable impact.\n✅ Use relevant keywords from the job description.\n✅ Keep formatting clean and simple (avoid graphics/tables).\n✅ Tailor each resume for the role, one-size-fits-all won’t work.\n✅ Want better results? Apply online AND network with hiring managers!\n\nFinally,\n👉 An ATS-friendly resume doesn’t just pass the ATS, it gets you noticed by recruiters!\n👉 ATS is just a tool, it doesn’t make hiring decisions!\n👉 ATS is not your enemy, it 