"📄 Resume Tips from a Recruiter (Take Them or Leave Them - could be my opinions only, so I welcome any other recruiters to chime in!)\n\nI’ve been deep in resume reviews over the past few weeks, and a few things have stood out. So, in the spirit of kindness and humor, here are some unsolicited tips to (hopefully) help you stand out in the best way possible:\n\n🎨 Go easy on the colors. A small splash of color? Cool. A rainbow? Distracting. Subtle and professional is the way to go.\n📜 Get to the good stuff quickly. I promise, most recruiters don’t spend much time on those paragraphs or “highlight” sections at the top. Put your experience front and center—I want to see what you’ve done without scrolling through a novel first.\n⚠️ Meet the minimum requirements (and be honest). If the role requires X, Y, and Z, please have X, Y, and Z. And lying on preliminary questions? Just don’t. It’s awkward for everyone.\n📊 Skip the charts, graphs, and graphics. They look fancy, but honestly, I usually scroll right past them. They don’t always add the value you think they do.\n✂️ Less is more. A focused, impactful resume beats one crammed with every single task you’ve ever done. Prioritize metrics and achievements—they’re your best friends.\n📸 No pictures, please. That space is better used for you—your experience, skills, and what makes you a great candidate.\n💡 I know the job market is tough right now, and it can be hard to know what works. I hope these tips are helpful as you polish up your resume. And know this: I’m rooting for you all!\nGood luck out there—you’ve got this! 💪\n…more"
