"CV/Resume Building: Your First Step to Career Success \n\nYour CV is often the first impression you make with a potential employer. Yet, many job seekers find themselves struggling with screening tests and not getting the calls they hope for. Instead of spending big on CV-building services, I believe the real investment is in time—and leveraging accessible tools like Canva, Adobe, or even simple MS Word.\nHere are a few key tips to help you boost your CV’s chances of passing those screening hurdles:\n\n1. Keep it Precise - Especially for freshers, it’s tempting to include everything. But remember, less is more. Seek advice from professionals in your field or a consultant to streamline your content and keep it relevant.\n\n2. Leverage AI Tools - Don’t miss out on the power of design! Use AI platforms to give your CV a polished, modern look. Plenty of templates are available, and a well-designed CV stands out.\n\n3. Formatting Matters - Ensure your CV is easy to read. Poor formatting—like mismatched fonts, inconsistent alignments, and heavy borders—can overwhelm the reader. Keep it clean and simple.\n\n4. Spell Check, Always - A CV with spelling or grammatical errors sends the wrong message. Always double-check and, if possible, ask someone else to review it too.\n\n5. Highlight Relevant Interests & Achievements - Tailor your CV to the role you're applying for. Sure, your singing talent is great, but if you’re applying for a finance role, highlighting your interest in business, finance, or the stock market will capture the recruiter’s attention.\n\n|| Brownie Tip ||\n\nUse an ATS-Friendly Format - Here's a tip most people don't know—make sure your CV is ATS-friendly (Applicant Tracking System). Many companies use ATS to filter CVs before they even reach a hiring manager. Stick to standard fonts, avoid images or complex formatting, and use keywords from the job description to increase your chances of passing the automated screening.\n\nRemember, a well-crafted CV isn’t just a list of qualifications—it’s your story in a nutshell. Spend the time to make it shine, and you’ll find yourself one step closer to that dream job.\n\nHuge thanks tofor sharing her insights on the concept of ""ATS/STAR format."" I really appreciate the knowledge and perspective!\n\n…more"
