"There is one phrase you should NEVER say to someone who is unemployed due to a layoff or something outside of their control.\n\n""Enjoy your time off!""\n\nAh yes....because losing your job is the all expenses paid vacation that NOBODY asked for.\n\nLet's be real:\n\n❌ Bills don't take a vacation. Rent, groceries, and student loans didn’t seem to get the memo that you're “off work.”\n\n❌ Job searching is a full-time job. Updating resumes, networking, and applying to 10-15 jobs a day isn't sipping margaritas on the beach.\n\n❌ Stress levels are high when you are unemployed and ""relaxing"" is tough when you are wondering how long your savings account will last.\n\nInstead of telling someone to ""enjoy"" their time off, try saying this instead:\n\n✅ ""How can I support you?""\n✅ ""Who can I introduce you to in my network that can help?""\n✅ ""If you need someone to talk to, don't hesitate to reach out.""\n\nBeing unemployed is anything but a vacation.\n\nThese jobseekers didn't ask for this time off.\n\nThey want to get back to work.\n\nLet's continue to support these jobseekers instead of giving them a ""silver lining"" speech.\n\n\n________________________________________________________________________________\n\nWant more authentic job searching tips and career advice in your news feed?\n\nSmash the 🔔 on my page so you don't miss my posts!\n\nIf you are spinning your wheels on your job search, my companyoffers hands-on career coaching sessions and other services including resume writing, interview practice, Linkedin Profile Optimization and more!\n\nSchedule your free 15-minute discovery call using the link at the top of my page and let's ROCK your job search!\n…more"
"DEAR JOB SEEKERS\n\nTHIS IS WHAT INCREASES YOUR CV SCORE ON THE APPLICANT TRACKING SYSTEM (ATS)\n\n1) SKILLS:\nYou can either have skills in your career objective, job bullet points, separate section or you can have skills in all the above mentioned.\n\n2) LINKEDIN URL:\nAdding a hyperlink to your Linkedin Profile will help you share information about yourself that might be too much for your CV.\n\n3) CONTACT NUMBER AND E-MAIL ADDRESS\nTip: Employers will use either of these two to communicate, make sure the email address spelling is correct and the numbers aren’t swapped around.\n\n4) FILE NAME:\nAlways use your First Name and Surname, using anything else might cause your CV to be discarded or marked off as suspicious.\n\n5) FILE SIZE\nThe file must be under 2 mb. If your CV is bigger than 2 mb you need to remove attachments (copies of qualifications, cover page pictures, photos) or simply re-save it in a different format that will allow for file compression.\n\n6) FILE TYPE:\nThe recommended file type to use is PDF (Not scanned), you must be able to highlight the text. Word can be used as well but PDF will cause the least problems.\n\n7) DATE FORMATTING:\nInclude the month and year for both the start and the end date, the most recent experience being at the top going down.\n\nHave a productive day job seekers, you’re all winners for not giving up!\n\n…more"
